 2.  INTRODUCTION 
 Westdeen  Holdings  Pty  Ltd  is  mining  mining  lease  M70/308  for  the  minerals  calcium 
 carbonate  (CaCO3)  and  magnesium  carbonate  (MgCO3).    These  minerals  occur  as 
 limesand,  the  primary  constituent  of  the  dunes  located  throughout  the  tenement.  
 Westdeen  markets  the  Cervantes  limesand  direct  from  the  pit  as  agricultural  lime  to 
 farmers  throughout  the  central  northern  wheatbelt  who  use  it  to  neutralise  soil  acidity 
 formed as a consequence of intensive farming. 
 Mining  on  M70/308  commenced  in  1988.    Relatively  small  tonnages  were  mined 
 through  the  late  1980’s  and  early  1990’s  due  an  ongoing  rural  recession  and  poor 
 market  acceptance.    Through  the  late  1990’s,  however,  there  was  a  marked 
 improvement  in  the  rural  economy  with  improved  farming  technology,  increased  crop 
 yields and higher export grain prices.  Positive extension campaigns on the need to lime 
 acid  soils  the  Department  of  Agriculture  and  Westdeen’s  continuing  research  and 
 promotion efforts have driven the increase in demand for limesand. 
 3.  LOCATION 
 Mining  lease  70/308  is  located  on  the  southern  Boundary  of  Government  (Apiculture 
 and  Conservation)  Reserve  36053  just  east  of  the  Cervantes  townsite’s  eastern 
 boundary.    Its  northern,  western and eastern boundaries border  the  Cervantes  Road, 
 the Pinnacles Road, and the Nambung National Park, respectively.  Its position relative 
 to local features is shown by map in Appendix 1 and tengraph plan in Appendix 2.

Mining at this location is an extremely simple operation.  A front-end loader is used to 
 dig limesand from the pit face.  Limesand is extracted down to the level of the adjacent 
 coastal  plain  (see  Appendices).    The  sand  is  either  screened  prior  to  stockpiling,  or 
 loaded straight into trucks for direct delivery to farm.  Trucks gain access to the minesite 
 by a track around 300m long leading in from the main bitumen road into Cervantes (See 
 appendices for photographs of mine entrance).  An elliptical entry/exit arrangement with 
 2  loading  ramps  is  maintained  to  ensure  appropriate  safety  standards  for  truck 
 movements and loading operations (see Appendices).   
 Only 21485 tonnes of limesand were mined and sold from Cervantes over the period 1 
 April 2006 to 31 March 2007.  This is 33% less than the 31,966 tonnes mined and sold 
 for  the  corresponding  period  last  year.    The  decrease  in  limesand  sold  by  Aglime  of 
 Australia was influenced by both lower prices farmer obtained for their crops, and the 
 emergence of ‘cut price, load yourself’ operations in nearby limesand deposits.  Despite 
 losing  sales,  our  company  policy  remains  as  always.    We  believe  it  is  imperative, 
 especially  from  a  safety  perspective  to  engage  the  services  of  professional  contract 
 loader  operators,  to  load  limesand  into  trucks  for  delivery  into  the  wheatbelt.    To  this 
 end, we must pay a reasonable fee for contract loading services.  The emergence of 
 cut-price operations that simply leave an old loader (often without approved load 
 cells) on site is a serious safety issue and needs to be addressed.

 8.   FUTURE MINING PLANS 
 Extractable reserves of limesand on M70/308 will probably be depleted in around 4-7 
 years  time.    Westdeen  is  currently  progressing  plans  to  relocate  the  Cervantes 
 operation to a new tenement with substantial reserves after that period.  The success 
 of this plan is dependant on:
